text.tspan: Wealth Management
ABN Amro
- Launched ABN GPT, a secure and compliant in-house version of ChatGPT, to better servce clients while improving efficiency. ABN GPT also helps developers in writing and documenting
software code, and to help employees generate text and retrieve
information from large documents
-The bank has transitioned to Microsoft Copilot Studio in partnership with Microsoft and Capgemini to develop Gen AI solutions for improved customer and employee interactions
-Additional use cases include docuement analysis, trade finance, call centre support, and software development
BNP
- Harnessing AI is one of the pillars of the tech side of BNP's 2025 plan. In 2024 BNP has already rolled out ~780 AI use cases and plans ~1000 use cases by 2025. According to BNP, AI plays
a key role in improving digital experience of customers and employees. BNP expects client relationships will be driven by a new balance between human and digital, managed by RMs
supported by enhanced expertise and digital tools as well as omni-channel and personalised interactions through AI and tech.
- Agreement with Mistral.ai signed in June 2024 - BNP sees GenAI as having significant potential to enhance client offering across sales, trading, research, and more - BNP expects this
parternship to allow hyper-personalised digital sevices for customers, and simplification of end-to-end processes.
- BNP Paribas has established a comprehensive Artificial Intelligence (AI) strategy since 2016, with significant acceleration in generative AI adoption since late 2022. The bank has
implemented over 800 AI use cases in production, with many more in development or testing.
- The bank is recognized as a leading European bank in AI startup investments and ranks third globally, notably fueling companies like Mistral AI
Credit Agricole
- In WM, rolled-out digital investment proposal tool in Switzerland and Luxembourg and new Customer Lifecycle Management (CLM) system in Luxembourg, as well as increased use of
Robotic Process Automation (RPA) and AI.
- Committed to training all Group employees in the uses of artificial intelligence, implementing an "IT 2025" program with a €1 billion investment over three years to accelerate technological
transformation
Julius Baer
. Upgraded RMs' tools by developing AI capabilities to create automation, boost efficency and scale
- Developed AI capabilities in-house, to better understand relationships with intermediaries and support RMs. These deliver predictions from models to assist RMs in helping intermediaries
serve their clients.
- Accelerating investments in AI and data to create new revenue opportunities. Use predictive data analysis to improve client retention and potential for gaining wallet share. Continued
investment in proprietary Mandate Solution Designer and advisory platform DiAS to scale tailored discretionary mandates and advisory process, which are already driving revenues and
improving margins.
- In Mar-22 received the Best Innovative Use of Artificial Intelligence and Best Innovative Client Solution awards at the Wealth Briefing European Awards 2022
- KYC / AML are another area of focus for AI use cases
- Julius Baer's Launchpad (innovation lab in Singapore) has been championing several initiatives, focusing on GenAI
KBC
-Kate is the firm's AI-based personal assistant for clients to use on its banking app. Kate also helps KBC's employees as it provides commercial steering, and allows the workfoce to focus on
more value added services to clients. The independent international consulting firm Sia Partners named KBC Mobile the top performing mobile banking app worldwide in 2024. Interestingly,
Kate's autonomy (i.e. the ability to service a client request end to end with no human intervention) continues to improve, having now reached 71% in Belgium from a 15% starting point in 2021.
- In 2023 KBC launched "Coin" to help clients "save time and earn money"
- KBC management estimates that Kate currently does approximately 300 FTE's worth of work per day
- Kate allows for 1-1.5% productivity gains per year, helping KBC maintain its goal of not growing costs more than 3% per year
Intesa
Intesa intends to use AI to unlock new business, increase operational efficiency and improve risk management. Intesa has 150 AI specialists and 80 AI use cases (almost 3x last year number),
targetting 300 specialists by 2025 and 140 use cases. AI to contribute an additional €100m to 2025 gross income (currently generating €0.5b) not including potential upside from adoption of
generative AI solutions.
- Approximately 230 dedicated AI specialists as of June 30, 2025, with plans to reach around 300 by the end of 2025
- Internal AI Academy with training activities involving over 1,500 participants
- Data & AI Community with over 9,000 members
- Specific performance improvements, such as AI solutions helping global relationship managers improve proposal conversion rates by 70%
UBS
- UBS is embedding AI solutions in client services and in supporting advisors, in order to drive advisors' productivity.
- UBS Group has developed an artificial intelligence tool to help it offer clients potential M&A deals, able to analyze a database of over 300,000 companies in less than half a minute. The tool
also identifies potential targets of activist campaigns by comparing the management tone of prepared presentations and Q&A situations. The bank said that it also sees potential use cases
for artificial intelligence to support M&A transactions for legal tasks and data-room work.
- UBS Red AI Assistants - Built on Azure AI and OpenAI, rolled out to 30,000 employees for advisor support and client engagement
- UBS has rolled out 50,000 Microsoft Copilot licenses to employees by end-March 2025
